<POSTER> Jeremy Cotton &lt;fullyalte...@hotmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-26T10:01:00 </POSTDATE>
Kids will pick up reading notation pretty quickly if you have them work with it in a few different ways.

After the first few lessons, I make students do their own tab if they want tab for something. I'll give them the note names and what string it is on and let them figure out where the note goes.  This seems to help them learn the fretboard more quickly.
The book I use for beginning students has backing tracks included on a CD.  Every few songs, I make them write their own melody to fit the backing tracks, and they have to write that in standard notation.  (Although I did once have a student decided to play a melody up around 9th position so I let her get away with tabbing it since we hadn't covered ledger lines yet.)
A lot of students learn quickly with flashcards- I've got 5 year olds who can ID notes from low E to high C as well as most common musical symbols because the flashcards are a game to them.

On the other hand, I teach a band class at an Elementary and Middle school that specializes in working with kids with learning disabilities, emotional problems, or physical handicaps.  I also have a few private students with reading issues. I try to find different ways to work with these kids.

JC

