Yes, we did this also in the string section of our community
orchestras.  The convention for us was Arabic numbers for fingers,
Roman numerals for position numbers.  We didn't indicate specific
strings (A vs. D vs. G vs. etc.) however.

Thus, a pencil is in every string player's instrument case, at least
those with sufficient experience to realize how much easier one's life
is made by being able to write down fingerings for one's part in the
arrangement.  Some even bring little springs or whatever to attach the
pencil to one's music stand.

On an aside, I am rereading Tony Levin's _Beyond the Bass Clef_.  I
just reached the chapter in which he says how important it is to be
able to hear in one's head the notes that one reads from sheet music.
He also describes the disadvantages of getting into the habit of
mapping the notes on paper to instrumental fingerings while completely
bypassing the ear.

